div.p:
We sow them [cinchonas] in greenhouses where we keep the young plants for some time, in order to harden them gradually to the variations in meteorological conditions that they will meet outside. We then put them in the open air, sheltering them by means of tree branches (
   Melaleuca ericifolia
). The earth that suits them is a light, rich and fresh earth composed at least in part of vegetable detritus. At the moment we have approximately ten thousand young Cinchona plants ready, for the most part, to be transplanted next autumn in the sheltered valleys of our mountains.
